ious art, Aron-Beller finds that narratives alleging that Jews committed violence against images of Christ, Mary, and the disciples flourished in Europe between the fifth and seventeenth centuries. She then explores how these narratives manifested differently across the continent and the centuries, finding that their potency reflected not Jewish actions per se, but Christians’ own concerns about slipping into idolatry when viewing depictions of religious figures. In addition, Aron-Beller considers Jews’ own attitudes toward Christian imagery and the ways in which they responded to and rejected—or embraced—such allegations. By examining how desecration allegations affected Jewish individuals and communities spanning Byzantium, medieval England, France, Germany, and early modern Spain and Italy, Aron-Beller demonstrates that this charge was a powerful expression of the Christian majority’s anxiety around committing idolatry and their eagerness to participate in practices of veneration that revolved around visual images—an anxiety that evolved through the centuries and persists to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian art and symbolismxMutilation, defacement, etczEuropexHistory2DLC. 0aChristian art and symbolismxMutilation, defacement, etc. 0aIdolatryzEuropexHistory2DLC. 0aIdolatry. 0aJudaismxControversial literaturexHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aJudaismxControversial literaturexHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAniconism.  aAntisemitic tropes.  aByzantium.  aEngland.  aEurope.  aIconoclasm.  aJewish Desecration of Christian Art.  aJewish attack of Christian images.  aJews and Blood.  aantisemitism.  ablood libel.  achrist on the cross.  achristian jewish relations.  aconversion narrative.  adivine punishment.  ahost desecration.  a